written instruments issued by banks stating that payments will be made on behalf of applicants to beneficiaries provided that the beneficiary fulfills all the conditions described in the instrument in essence the effect of an lc is to substitute the credit of a bank which is generally well known for the credit of an applicant which is either not as well known or not considered to be adequate by the beneficiary in issuing the lc the bank becomes entitled to reimbursement from the applicant for any payments that the bank properly makes the applicant may provide collateral to the bank to secure the repayment of the reimbursement obligation or the bank may simply rely on the applicants promise to pay the bank receives fees for issuing and handling lcs principle of independence as professionals bankers have a duty to protect not only the interest of their banks but also their customers interests applicants are often unaware of the risk undertaken when they apply for an lc applicants must be made aware that the relationship between an issuing bank and the beneficiary is an entirely separate contractual relationship unlike that between the applicant and the beneficiary the bank deals in documents only not merchandise or performance and it therefore cannot ensure that the underlying transaction has been fulfilled to the satisfaction of the applicant when all stipulated documents are presented the issuing bank must pay the beneficiary the applicant must not rely on the lc for protection from the beneficiarys performance problems the banks responsibility is only to examine documents with reasonable care and to ascertain that they appear to comply with the requirements of the lc once the lc is issued the applicant faces the risk that the lc may be paid through fraudulent actions of the beneficiary another aspect of the independence of the relationships of the three parties involved relates to amendments of the lc proposed amendments must be acceptable to all parties issuer applicant and beneficiary to be considered in effect no party has the power to make unilateral changes in the terms of an irrevocable lc two categories lcs issued by my bank fall into two broad categories  commercial traderelated and standby commercial lcs commercial or traderelated lcs are used to carry out specific trade transactions involving the sale or purchase of goods sellers of goods desire to know that if they perform according to the terms of their agreement with the purchaser that is deliver the product they will be paid the presence of the lc from a financially strong third party gives the seller beneficiary that assurance by providing this assurance to the beneficiary the bank obviously assumes credit risk as previously mentioned lcs rely on documents not verified performance for a beneficiary to claim payment under an lc the beneficiarys documents must conform exactly to those required by the lc … subscribe today subscribe to questia and enjoy full access to this article and over  million more from academic journals magazines and newspapers over  books access to powerful writing and research tools article details publication journal of commercial lending volumeissue vol  no  publication date may  contributors harton h lynn subjects letters of creditlaws regulations and rules commercial loansmanagement bank managementmethods subscribe today subscribe to questia and enjoy full access to this article and over  million more from academic journals magazines and newspapers over  books access to powerful writing and research tools article details publication journal of commercial lending volumeissue vol  no  publication date may  contributors harton h lynn subjects letters of creditlaws regulations and rules commercial loansmanagement bank managementmethods search our library  search by author search by  keyword title author subject publisher results should have  all of these words any of these words this exact phrase none of these words keyword searches may als